<Base title="Historical continuity" compactHeader={true}>
  <p class="ar-title" lang="ar" dir="rtl">السنة عبر التاريخ</p>
  <h2>Historical continuity</h2>
  <p class="summary">A short historical map: what "Ahl al-Sunnah wa-l-Jamāʿa" originally referred to, how Sunnī theology developed across the first ten centuries of Islam, and where the modern movements — Wahhābism/Salafism, Deobandīsm, Barelvīsm, the Sufi orders — sit in that genealogy.</p>

  <h3>The original term: Ahl al-Sunnah wa-l-Jamāʿa</h3>
  <p>The phrase Ahl al-Sunnah wa-l-Jamāʿa — "the people of the Sunnah and the community" — emerges in the second Hijri century as a self-description distinguishing the mainstream of Muslims from the Khawārij (who broke from the community over the question of major sin), the Shīʿa (who held a different theology of legitimate authority), the Muʿtazila (who used Greek-derived rationalism to read the Qurʾān), and the Murjiʾa (who held that imān is divorced from action). Each of these groups was understood at the time as a deviation from the way of the Prophet ﷺ and his Companions; what was left after these subtractions was Ahl al-Sunnah wa-l-Jamāʿa — the broad continuity of the Companions' practice and creed.</p>
  <p>Crucially, this term was an <em>exclusion</em> — it described who was <em>not</em> one of the recognized splinter groups — rather than a positive school. The Companions and the Salaf themselves did not have a written ʿaqīdah manual; what they affirmed was passed orally and lived in practice. The work of organising that creed into systematic written form belongs to the next four centuries.</p>

  <h3>Development of Sunnī theology — the 2nd to 5th Hijri centuries</h3>
  <p>Three pressures drove the formal articulation of Sunnī ʿaqīdah:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>The Muʿtazilī challenge.</strong> The Muʿtazila brought Greek philosophical categories — particularly questions about the createdness of the Qurʾān, free will and predestination, and the rationality of the divine attributes — into Islamic discourse. Their pressure during the <em>miḥna</em> (the inquisition under the Abbasid caliph al-Maʾmūn, 833 CE) forced a reactive defense of Sunnī positions. Imam Aḥmad ibn Ḥanbal's stand under torture, refusing to affirm the createdness of the Qurʾān, became foundational for the textual-affirmation tradition.</li>
    <li><strong>The Greek philosophical pressure.</strong> The translation of Aristotle, Plotinus, and others into Arabic in the 9th century placed Muslims in conversation with a thousand years of Hellenic metaphysics. The figure most associated with this pressure is the philosopher al-Kindī (d. ~870 CE) and after him al-Fārābī (d. 950 CE) and Ibn Sīnā (d. 1037 CE). Defending Islamic ʿaqīdah against their challenges required engaging their conceptual vocabulary.</li>
    <li><strong>The internal need to systematize.</strong> As the umma expanded across cultures, Muslims who were not native Arabic speakers needed clear creedal formulations. Children of converts, scholars in Khurasan, fiqh students in Egypt — all needed creeds they could memorize and pass on.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>From these pressures emerged three systematic formulations of Sunnī ʿaqīdah, all considered orthodox:</p>

  <p><strong>The Atharī school</strong> — text-based, beginning with Imam Aḥmad ibn Ḥanbal (d. 855 CE) and continued by his students and the Ḥanbalī tradition. The Atharī methodology is to affirm whatever the Qurʾān and Sunnah affirm, in the apparent meaning of the words but without specifying a modality (<em>bilā kayf</em>), and to refrain from kalām-style argumentation. The classical Atharī ʿaqīdah is found in works like Imam Aḥmad's <em>Uṣūl al-Sunnah</em>, Ibn Qudāma al-Maqdisī's <em>Lumʿat al-Iʿtiqād</em>, and the later Ḥanbalī manuals.</p>

  <p><strong>The Ashʿarī school</strong> — Imam Abū al-Ḥasan al-Ashʿarī (d. 936 CE), originally a Muʿtazilī who returned to mainstream Sunnism. He systematized Sunnī creed using kalām techniques to refute the Muʿtazila on their own terms. The school continued through al-Bāqillānī (d. 1013 CE), al-Juwaynī (d. 1085 CE), al-Ghazālī (d. 1111 CE), al-Rāzī (d. 1209 CE), al-Āmidī (d. 1233 CE), al-Bayḍāwī (d. 1286 CE), al-Ījī (d. 1355 CE), al-Taftāzānī (d. 1390 CE), and al-Jurjānī (d. 1413 CE). Most Shāfiʿīs and Mālikīs across the medieval Islamic world were Ashʿarī in creed.</p>

  <p><strong>The Māturīdī school</strong> — Imam Abū Manṣūr al-Māturīdī of Samarqand (d. 944 CE). Working in Khurasan and Transoxiana, he developed a parallel kalām-based Sunnī creed, slightly more rationalist than Ashʿarī in some specific positions (the role of reason in moral knowledge, the relationship between divine attributes). The school continued through al-Nasafī (d. 1142 CE), al-Bazdawī (d. 1099 CE), and the Ottoman ʿaqīdah tradition. Most Ḥanafīs across the Muslim world were Māturīdī.</p>

  <h3>The four-century mainstream consensus (5th to 12th Hijri / 11th to 18th CE)</h3>
  <p>From roughly the 11th to the 18th century, mainstream Sunnism was characterized by an institutional consensus: a Muslim followed one of the four madhāhib of fiqh (Ḥanafī, Mālikī, Shāfiʿī, Ḥanbalī) and adopted the corresponding creedal school (Ashʿarī, Māturīdī, or Atharī). The major institutions of Islamic learning — al-Azhar in Cairo, the Niẓāmiyyah madrasas, the Ḥaramayn before the modern era, the Ottoman religious establishment, the South Asian Mughal madrasas, the Mauritanian and Yemeni traditional schools — all transmitted this consensus.</p>
  <p>Tasawwuf (Sufism), in this period, was not a separate sect but a complementary discipline focused on the inward purification of the soul. Major Sufi figures like Imam al-Ghazālī, ʿAbd al-Qādir al-Jīlānī, ʿUmar al-Suhrawardī, and Muḥyī al-Dīn ibn ʿArabī were also mainstream Sunnī jurists in one of the four madhāhib. The Sufi orders (ṭuruq) — Qādiriyyah, Naqshbandiyyah, Shādhiliyyah, and others — operated within the framework of the four madhāhib of fiqh and the three creedal schools.</p>

  <h3>The 18th-century inflection: Wahhābism / Salafism</h3>
  <p>Muḥammad ibn ʿAbd al-Wahhāb's revivalist project in 18th-century Najd presented itself as a return to the methodology of the Salaf. From the perspective of the established four-madhhab Sunnī ʿulamāʾ of his time — Mecca, Medina, Damascus, Cairo, Istanbul — he was charged with departing from the established Ḥanbalī school's methodology, with anathematising fellow Sunnī Muslims for practices the four madhāhib had permitted (tawassul, ziyārah, the recitation of the Prophet's ﷺ life), and with collaborating with the Saudi state in violent campaigns against other Muslims. The first mufti of Mecca, Aḥmad ibn Zaynī Daḥlān (d. 1886), wrote one of the earliest formal refutations: <em>Fitnat al-Wahhābiyya</em>. The Ottoman ʿulamāʾ as a whole rejected the movement.</p>
  <p>This is not the same as saying the movement was "non-Sunnī" — it positioned itself as Sunnī, claimed Ḥanbalī fiqh, and invoked the Salaf. What it broke with was the institutional, four-madhhab, three-creedal-school consensus that had defined mainstream Sunnism for the previous seven centuries.</p>

  <h3>The 19th-century South Asian reform movements</h3>
  <p>Two parallel revivalist movements emerged in 19th-century South Asia, both framing themselves as Sunnī continuations. Both are Ḥanafī in fiqh and Māturīdī in creed.</p>
  <p><strong>Deobandīsm</strong> (Dar al-Ulum Deoband, founded 1866) emerged from the trauma of the failed Indian Rebellion of 1857 as a revivalist movement focused on traditional Islamic education, ḥadīth, and a careful guarding of the Sharīʿah against syncretic Hindu-Muslim cultural practices. Its leading figures (Muhammad Qasim Nanautawi, Rashid Ahmad Gangohi, Ashraf Ali Thanawi) were full Sufis — Naqshbandī-Chishtī Sufis specifically — and the movement preserved Sufism as integral to Islamic life. Deobandīs are theologically Māturīdī, Ḥanafī in fiqh, but adopt a more text-cautious position on certain practices (mawlid celebrations, certain forms of group dhikr) than the Barelvī school.</p>
  <p><strong>Barelvīsm</strong> (Bareilly, founded under Aḥmad Riḍā Khān, d. 1921) emerged in parallel as a defense of traditional South Asian Sufi-Sunnī practice against Deobandī cautions and Wahhābī attacks. Barelvīs are also Ḥanafī Māturīdī, but they affirm and defend mawlid celebrations, tawassul through the Prophet ﷺ and the awliyāʾ, and the broad practice of grave visitation. The two movements have polemicised against each other for over a century, but both reject the Salafī rejection of madhhab-based fiqh and Ashʿarī/Māturīdī creed.</p>

  <h3>The 20th century — globalisation</h3>
  <p>Two pivots define the 20th-century reshaping of Sunnism:</p>
  <p><strong>Rashīd Riḍā</strong> (d. 1935) — an Egyptian student of Muḥammad ʿAbduh — increasingly aligned in his later years with Wahhābī ʿaqīdah and used his journal <em>al-Manār</em> to make Najdī revivalism intelligible and attractive to a modern Arab readership. Through Riḍā's circle, Salafism became a transnational intellectual movement rather than a purely Najdī one.</p>
  <p><strong>The Saudi state oil revenues</strong> (post-1973) — funded mosques, scholarships, books, satellite-TV preachers, and an institutional infrastructure on a scale unprecedented in Islamic history. The shape of contemporary global English-language Salafism — its translation projects, its Ramadān satellite programming, its preachers in non-Arab Muslim countries — is in large part the cultural-export face of this funding.</p>

  <h3>Where each movement sits today</h3>
  <p>Surveying the global Sunnī landscape:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Traditional four-madhhab Sunnism</strong> with one of the three classical creedal schools (Ashʿarī, Māturīdī, Atharī) — still the institutional centre of al-Azhar, the Mauritanian schools, the Yemeni Ḥaḍramī tradition, traditional Indonesian and Malaysian Islam, and Western traditional-Sunnī networks like SeekersGuidance and Zaytuna College.</li>
    <li><strong>Salafism</strong> — concentrated in Saudi-funded institutions but globalised; further subdivided into "purist Salafīs" who avoid politics (e.g., Madkhalīs), "Ṣurūrī" Salafīs who entered Islamist politics, and various reformist Salafī tendencies.</li>
    <li><strong>Deobandī Ḥanafī Māturīdī Sunnism</strong> — the dominant institutional form in South Asia, with a global diaspora; theologically conservative on ʿaqīdah, more cautious than Barelvīs on Sufi practices.</li>
    <li><strong>Barelvī Ḥanafī Māturīdī Sunnism</strong> — likewise dominant in South Asia and the Pakistani diaspora; affirms and defends the full Sufi-Sunnī devotional repertoire including mawlid, tawassul, and ziyārah.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>This site argues that the three classical creedal schools — Ashʿarī, Māturīdī, Atharī — together with the four madhāhib of fiqh and the inherited Sufi tradition, constitute the historical mainstream of Ahl al-Sunnah. The Salafī movement, despite invoking the term <em>Salaf</em>, is a specific 18th-century revivalist project whose positions on multiple specific questions (mawlid, tawassul, ziyārah, kalām) depart from the institutional consensus that came before it. The topic pages on this site work out the specific points in detail.</p>

  <h3>Further reading</h3>
  <p class="reading">
    Wilfred Madelung, <em>The Succession to Muḥammad</em> (Cambridge, 1997) — early Islamic political-theological history. ·
    W. Montgomery Watt, <em>The Formative Period of Islamic Thought</em> (Edinburgh, 1973) — origins of the early sects and theological schools. ·
    Marshall Hodgson, <em>The Venture of Islam</em> (Chicago, 1974) — the standard three-volume history of Islamic civilisation. ·
    Khaled El-Rouayheb, <em>Islamic Intellectual History in the Seventeenth Century</em> (Cambridge, 2015) — late premodern Sunnī theology and ʿaqīdah. ·
    Jonathan Brown, <em>Misquoting Muhammad</em> (Oneworld, 2014) — contemporary tensions across traditional Sunnism, Salafism, and modernity. ·
    Hamid Algar, <em>Wahhabism: A Critical Essay</em> (Islamic Publications International, 2002) — academic Sunnī critique. ·
    David Commins, <em>The Wahhabi Mission and Saudi Arabia</em> (I.B. Tauris, 2006) — neutral academic history.
  </p>
